\section{Mapping Node}

As can be seen in figure \ref{ImplOverview} the mapping node has a central position in the system. It is also the largest node in terms written code. This section is split into four parts, the structure of the implementation, how the incoming messages are processed, code executed regularly to publish messages or detect map switches and the handling of service requests.

\subsection{Mapping Node Stucture}

In figure \ref{mapping overview} the general structure of the mapping node is show. The TopologicalMapper is the main class in this structure, holding a RoomMapper for every room. The RoomMapper is derived from the SlamGmapper class, which does the 2D SLAM using Gmapping. Instead of putting the other types of maps into the particles, which would have resulted in making major changes in Gmapping, the RoomMapper holds a separate mapping class for every type of map and every particle. 

\begin{figure}
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.9\textwidth,clip]{figures/MappingClassDiagram.pdf}
  \caption[Mapping node structure]{An overview over structure of the mapping node}
  \label{mapping overview}
\end{figure}

In listing \ref{TopologicalMapper} the most important member variables and methods of the TopologicalMapper are shown. Beside an array of RoomMapper it has also variables to keep track of the current room and which rooms are explored. The latter is important in the generation of the high-level attributes needed by the high-level planner. The variable topology stores the last   Also the current action is stored to decide if the doors have to be blocked by virtual obstacles. The AsyncSpinner is used to run the service callbacks in another thread. This is important because the generation of the Object-Probability-Map and the calculation of the high-level attributes might take up to one second, which would block the mapping for too long.

The TopologicalMapper contains the run() function, which is started during initialization and returns when the node is terminated. Also the message are received in this node. This way the they can be passed to the current mapper and so no enabling and disabling of callbacks in the room{\_}mappers is needed. The service callbacks are also done by the TopologicalMapper. The details about these callbacks are given later.

\begin{minipage}{\linewidth}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=TopologicalMapper,frame=single, label=TopologicalMapper]
   //members
   RoomMapper[] room_mappers
   int current_mapper
   bool[] room_explored
   topologicalMapServiceResponse topology
   bool[] room_changed
   int current_action
   
   AsyncSpinner service_spinner
   
   //methods
   run()
   
   pointcloudCb()
   laserCallback()
   doorwayCb()
   visionCb()
   currentActionCb()
   exploredCb()
   
   topologicalMapServiceCb()
   objectMapServiceCb()
   
\end{lstlisting}
\end{minipage} 

The ROS-node for Gmapping was the starting point for implementing the SlamGmapper node. This node is the interface to the Gmapping library used for 2D SLAM. The particle filter it holds is derived from the original particle filter to add the functionality needed in map switching. The publishing of the current pose of the robot is done in a separate thread because this has to be published regularly. The processLaser() function of the currently active RoomMapper is called when a new laser scan arrives and does the update of the particles and their maps.

\begin{minipage}{\linewidth}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=SlamGmapper,frame=single, label=SlamGmapper]
   //members
   ParticleFilter[] particle_filter   
   Thread transform_publish_thread
   
   //methods
   processLaser()
   
\end{lstlisting}
\end{minipage}

The RoomMapper class is the main class for the mapping within a room. It inherits the 2D SLAM functionality of the SlamGmapper class and also holds the mappers for all the other information. If a RoomMapper is active it receives the messages gathered by the TopologicalMapper. Those messages are partially processed by the RoomMapper and then forwarded to all the special mappers. The creation of the 3D map is the most expensive part of the mapping. To avoid it slowing down the other mappers it is done in a separate thread. The activate() and  deactivate() functions are called during the map switch.

\begin{minipage}{\linewidth}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=RoomMapper,frame=single, label=RoomMapper]
   //members
   OctoMapper[] octo_mapper
   ObjectMapper[] object_mapper
   RoomTypeMapper[] roomtype_mapper
   DoorwayMapper[] doorway_mapper
   
   Thread octo_mapper_thread
   
   //methods
   activate()
   deactivate()
   
   processCloud()
   processDoorway()
   processVision()
   
\end{lstlisting}
\end{minipage} 

The OctoMapper is based on the code of the octomap{\_}server node. It is the interface to the OctoMap library. The processCloud() function is called to update the 3D map with the information in the point cloud. The projectDown() function is used to create the 2D map containing the obstacles found in this map.

\begin{minipage}{\linewidth}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=OctoMapper,frame=single, label=OctoMapper]
   //members
   Octree octree
      
   //methods   
   processCloud()  
   projectDown()
   
\end{lstlisting}
\end{minipage} 

The RoomTypeMapper contains 60 RoomTypeMaps, one for each room type. These RoomTypeMaps are implemented using OpenCV's cv::Mat to represent the two dimensional grid. The probabilityMap contains the probabilities for the given room type for all cells in the map. The seenCountMap is used to determine which cells were seen. In addition the resolution and the origin are stored, so transforming world coordinates to map coordinates and vice verse is possible. The updateMaps() function is called with the result of the vision as a parameter, so the maps can be updated.

\begin{minipage}{\linewidth}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=RoomTypeMapper,frame=single, label=RoomTypeMapper]
   //members
   RoomTypeMap[] room_type_maps
      cv::Mat probabilityMap
      cv::Mat seenCountMap
      float resolution
      cv::Point origin
   
   //methods
   updateMaps()
   
\end{lstlisting}
\end{minipage} 


The ObjectMapper contains 61 ObjectMaps, one for each object type. These ObjectMaps are implemented as an array of OpenCV's cv::Mat. Each cv::Mat is a slice of the 3D map grid map. The probabilityMap, the seenCountMap, the resolution and the origin are similar to in the RoomTypeMap. The updateMaps() function is called with the result of the vision as a parameter, so the maps can be updated.

\begin{minipage}{\linewidth}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=ObjectMapper,frame=single, label=ObjectMapper]
   //members
   ObjectMap object_maps
      cv::Mat[] probabilityMap
      cv::Mat[] seenCountMap  
      float resolution
      cv::Point origin
      
      updateMaps()
      
   //methods
   updateMap()
   
\end{lstlisting}
\end{minipage} 

The DoorwayMapper holds a list containing all doorways found in this room. Beside the pose in the room the Door class contains information about its corresponding doorway in the other room. This design of representing links between rooms was chosen as this is easier for the mapping of doorway poses. This is more important than an easy access to the links between rooms because the links are only needed when the topological map is needed or when the room is switched. The processDoorway() function receives is called containing the array of detected doorways.

\begin{minipage}{\linewidth}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python, caption=DoorwayMapper,frame=single, label=DoorwayMapper]
   //members
   Doorway[] doorways
      Pose pose
      Pose[] pose_array
      int id
      int counterpart_id
      int this_room
      int other_room
   
   //methods
   processDoorway()
   
\end{lstlisting}
\end{minipage} 

